But Lucretius does not believe that the only serious business ol life is sensual pleasure, and will not say, ‘Let us eat and drink, for to·morrow we die.³ To his austere and noble nature this argument made no appeal, and he only mentions it to dismiss it with contempt².

What then does Lucretius say? He can promise no heaven hereafter3 but he tells men that if they have nothing to hope, they have also nothing to sear, beyond the grave.

It cannot be doubted that in the life-time of Lucretius the great majority of his countrymen believed in some form os future existence³. Nor was this belief confined to the simple and ignorant.
